<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Bursera microphylla </i>is a small tree to 8 m tall with pinnately compound, aromatic leaves. The bark on the main truck is copper colored and exfoliates in sheets, and the branches are cherry red colored and have oily sap. The lower trunk thickens with age. Plants are drought deciduous and store water in the parenchyma and wood of the photosynthetic branches and trunks. They bloom in the summer and produce drupes, suggesting birds as a vector to disperse seeds (Turner et al. 1995). <i>B. microphylla </i>is a CNPS list 2.3 plant. <br/>
<br/>
In California, <i>B. microphylla </i>occurs scattered and intermixed with shrubs, usually associated with the <i>Larrea tridentata-Ambrosia dumosa </i>or <i>L. tridentata- Encelia farinosa </i>alliances. Stands occur on sandy alluvium and mixed granitic slopes. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
