    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        
            <p>About 20 populations of <i>Bursera microphylla</i> exist, mostly in Anza-Borrego State Park (Schoenherr and Burk 2007), though most are not sufficiently dense to map. In Baja California, Peinado et al. (2007) found<i> B. microphylla</i> as an associate of <i>Maytenus phyllanthoides</i> stands in coastal dune slopes and sea-exposed, rocky slopes.</p>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Colorado Desert</b> (322Cb). Three mapped stands of <i>B. microphylla</i> in the Colorado Desert occur in the Santa Rosa Mountains, Starfish Cove, and Torote Canyon (Keeler-Wolf et al. 1998b).</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Mountains and Valleys</b> (M262Bp). No description available</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
